  abstract={The collaboration between MEC and UAVs has introduced groundbreaking opportunities for effective data processing and computation services in the domain of the IoT. Despite this advancement, the existence of an active eavesdropper introduces notable security vulnerabilities to the computation process of MDs. This research presents an effective strategy designed to reduce energy consumption in a secure WEB 3.0-driven resource allocation and trajectory optimization in UAV-Assisted MEC Networks that faces the challenge of a UAV eavesdropper to ensure transparent and tamper-resistant forensic records, enabling trust and accountability. By guaranteeing secure computation of all MDs data, the network attains its desired energy consumption targets through optimization of trajectories and resources, considering factors such as time, local computation, and offloading computation distribution. A WEB 3.0, blockchain-based forensic is used to address this issue because standard approaches are ineffective. Results from simulations exhibit that the proposed strategy surpasses the benchmark in lowering the network’s energy consumption and cyber threats. Numerical results shows that the proposed scheme achieves a 76.29% reduction in reward variance and reduced the energy consumption by around 87.41% as compared to the existing baseline schemes.},
